So there&#39;s multiple ways you can do this.  The most straightforward way is just adding a new property manually.
```js
const sampleObject = {
  child1: [
    {id: &#39;id1&#39;},
    {id: &#39;id2&#39;}
  ]
}

sampleObject.child2 = [{id: &#39;id3&#39;}]
```

If this doesn&#39;t work in your circumstance, you could try `Object.defineProperty()`. [read more about Object.defineProperty](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/defineProperty)

```js
const sampleObject = {
  child1: [
    {id: &#39;id1&#39;},
    {id: &#39;id2&#39;}
  ]
}

Object.defineProperty(sampleObject, &#39;child2&#39;, {
  value: [{id: &#39;id3&#39;}]
})
```

Finally, if you want to use `Object.assign()` you can, but this is mostly for merging two or more objects.  This is a good way to provide defaults, and then optionally override them. [read more about Object.assign](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/assign)

```js
const sampleObject = {
  child1: [
    {id: &#39;id1&#39;},
    {id: &#39;id2&#39;}
  ]
}

const sampleObject2 = {
  child2: [
    {id: &#39;id3&#39;}
  ]
}

Object.assign(sampleObject, sampleObject2)
```

Update: as mentioned by @Ryan Nghiem, you can also use the spread operator (`...`) in a similar way, though I would discourage reassigning the original variable.  This will &quot;spread&quot; out each property from the original object as properties of the new one. [read more about the spread operator](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax)

```js
const sampleObject = {
  child1: [
    {id: &#39;id1&#39;},
    {id: &#39;id2&#39;}
  ]
}

const sampleObject2 = {
  ...sampleObject,
  child2: [
    {id: &#39;id3&#39;}
  ]
}
```

